  _eventName: 'Massive strikes: the country paralyzed, the population forced to find
    alternatives'
  _date: September 26, 2024
  _subheading: For several days now, France has been rocked by a strike of historic
    proportions. Trains, metros, buses and even some flights have ground to a halt,
    while thousands of workers have taken to the streets to defend their rights in
    the face of announced reforms. The country, which is literally at a standstill,
    is plunged into a mobility crisis that is forcing everyone to improvise solutions
    for getting around in other ways.
  _coverImage: {fileID: 21300000, guid: 63e7cdb0f96db1612b9b3ce7e5ed8081, type: 3}
  _captionImage: Aenean malesuada gravida diam, non tempus eros elementum vel. Phasellus
    pulvinar non nisl in sceler.
  _description: 'A reinvented daily life for workers: With public transport out of
    service, the French are doubling their ingenuity to get to work. Cities are seeing
    an explosion in travel by bike, scooter or even carpooling. In large cities,
    VTC platforms and self-service bikes are full from the early hours of the day.
    Some companies, anticipating the difficulties of their employees, have made their
    hours more flexible and implemented teleworking to reduce travel. Traffic jams
    and forced march in city centers: The roads are saturated, and traffic jams stretch
    for kilometers on the outskirts of large cities, creating chaotic traffic. In
    some neighborhoods, residents have no choice but to walk to reach their destination.
    "I had to walk for an hour to get to my office," says a Parisian employee. Many
    are organizing themselves into walking groups or taking turns to offer impromptu
    carpooling, a solidarity that helps to overcome the situation. A major economic
    and social impact: The strikes are having a severe impact on businesses and professionals,
    with delivery delays and reduced traffic in commercial areas. Local authorities
    are increasing their calls for patience and urging people to limit non-essential
    travel. Meanwhile, discussions between unions and the government are intensifying,
    but no agreement seems in sight yet. The country remains suspended, hoping for
    a favorable outcome to end this blockage that weighs on society as a whole. In
    the meantime, France continues to reinvent itself to the rhythm of demonstrations
    and traffic jams, determined to face this unprecedented mobility crisis day after
    day. For several days, an unprecedented wave of strikes has paralyzed France,
    plunging the country into an unprecedented mobility crisis. Public transport
    is almost at a standstill: trains, metros, buses, and even some tram lines are
    no longer running. The unions, which are demanding better wages and improved
    working conditions, have decided to toughen up the movement, forcing users to
    look for alternatives. For workers and students, this strike poses daily challenges.
    Traffic jams have intensified, bicycles and scooters have multiplied on the streets,
    and carpooling is becoming an increasingly popular option. Some, who have no
    other choice, are even patient and walk several kilometers to get to their workplace.
    Companies, for their part, are adapting as best they can: widespread teleworking,
    staggered hours, videoconference meetings, everything is in place to minimize
    the impact of this paralysis. The current strikes are raising tensions, and users
    are expressing a mixture of support and frustration. On the one hand, many understand
    the demands of the strikers, often from public sectors that have been struggling
    for a long time. On the other hand, the scale of the daily impact is pushing
    some to express their exasperation in the face of this situation that has become
    almost unsustainable. In this context, the authorities are trying to engage in
    dialogue to avoid a stalemate, but the normal resumption of services still seems
    far away. In the meantime, the daily lives of the French are adapting, demonstrating
    once again their resilience, but also the fragility of our society when the wheels
    of transport come to a standstill. //Effect: drop in popularity of public transport
    / No public transport available (time over 2 weeks)'
